{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17411395","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17411395"},"attributes":{"position":9,"marks":1,"answeredAt":null,"options":[],"response":null,"finalizedAt":null},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"session":{"data":{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11407"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473828","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473828"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:15:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:15:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11407"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questionSessions","id":"1260986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionSessions/1260986"},"attributes":{"startedAt":"2025-09-28T06:24:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T07:02:58+09:30","sessionType":"qbank","questionStatus":"all","difficulty":[],"timeLimit":null,"questionCount":13,"questionsAnswered":0,"marksTotal":0,"marksAttainable":0,"marksAttempted":0,"finishedAt":"2025-09-28T06:25:33+09:30","resultsAvailable":true,"score":0,"questionsCorrect":0,"marksCorrect":0},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"pack":{"data":{"type":"packs","id":"5"}},"exam":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questions","id":"11407","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11407"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.21,0.55,0.06,0.05,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4043"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48918"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4043","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4043"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11407"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33918"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"5002"},{"type":"tags","id":"11471"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4640"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6299"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42593"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44100"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/48918"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 13-month-old boy presents to the cardiology outpatient department following referral by his General Practitioner. The referral was made after the discovery of a murmur during the child\u0027s 12-month vaccination visit. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. His height is at the 74th percentile and weight at the 68th percentile for his age. Auscultation of the praecordium reveals a mid-systolic murmur best heard over the upper left sternal border, with fixed splitting of S2. The remainder of the physical examination is unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Ventricular septal defect","Atrial septal defect","Hypertrophic cardiomyopathy","Mitral stenosis","Patent ductus arteriosus"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation in this case is most consistent with an \u003Cstrong\u003Eatrial septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E (ASD). The typical murmur for ASD is an ejection systolic or mid-systolic murmur heard best over the upper left sternal border. The fixed splitting of S2, which does not become single with expiration, is a hallmark finding in ASD. This occurs due to the equalisation of respiratory effects on both right and left ventricular output secondary to the presence of an atrial defect. ASDs are often asymptomatic in infancy and early childhood, which aligns with this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eventricular septal defect\u003C/strong\u003E (VSD) typically presents with a pansystolic (harsh) murmur heard best over the lower left sternal border. It is not usually associated with fixed splitting of the second heart sound. VSDs can sometimes close spontaneously in infancy, unlike ASDs which rarely close on their own.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHypertrophic cardiomyopathy\u003C/strong\u003E (HCM) can produce a systolic ejection murmur, but it is not typically associated with fixed splitting of the second heart sound. HCM usually presents later in childhood or adulthood. Other suggestive features may include pre-syncope, syncope, dyspnoea or palpitations, particularly on exertion, as well as a family history of sudden cardiac death.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitral stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E typically produces a mid-diastolic murmur, not a mid-systolic murmur as described in this case. It is also rare in children, usually occurring as a late complication of rheumatic fever or as a congenital condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Epatent ductus arteriosus\u003C/strong\u003E (PDA) typically produces a continuous \u0027machinery\u0027 murmur, best heard at the left infraclavicular area. PDAs are usually diagnosed and treated in early infancy, making this diagnosis less likely in a 13-month-old child.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["An asymptomatic mid-systolic murmur with fixed splitting of S2 in a child is most likely to be an atrial septal defect.","Atrial septal defects are often asymptomatic in infancy and early childhood, but can lead to complications if left untreated."],"references":["Bradley EA, Zaidi AN. Atrial Septal Defect. Cardiol Clin. 2020; 38:317-24."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33918"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11407"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"33918","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/33918"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-19T14:22:02+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-07-19T14:22:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4043"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"48918"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"2","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/2"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec0","name":"Cardiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id